{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17588528","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17588528"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T09:09:54+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T09:09:54+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15166"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15166","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15166"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7857"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66770"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7857","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7857"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15166"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52224"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"15"},{"type":"tags","id":"30"},{"type":"tags","id":"36"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4183"},{"type":"tags","id":"4933"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"6488"},{"type":"tags","id":"8115"},{"type":"tags","id":"8133"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"19154"},{"type":"contributions","id":"19157"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22318"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66770","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/66770"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EVarious imaging modalities can be considered for investigating potential renal tract problems.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate indication for renal ultrasonography?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Isolated low serum creatinine","Isolated proteinuria less than 1 g/day","Single uncomplicated urinary tract infection","Transient microscopic haematuria","Visible haematuria"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003ERenal ultrasonography is an important non-invasive imaging modality for evaluating the urinary tract. \u003Cstrong\u003EVisible haematuria\u003C/strong\u003E requires thorough investigation as it may indicate serious underlying pathology such as malignancy, stones, or structural abnormalities. Ultrasound can identify kidney masses, stones, hydronephrosis, and assess kidney size and echogenicity. Here is an example of a mass in the right kidney (Image)\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn \u003Cstrong\u003Eisolated low serum creatinine\u003C/strong\u003E is not an indication for renal imaging. Low creatinine may reflect reduced muscle mass or poor nutrition rather than kidney pathology.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Esingle uncomplicated urinary tract infection\u003C/strong\u003E in an adult does not require imaging. However, imaging would be indicated for recurrent infections or complicated cases with systemic symptoms or underlying risk factors.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETransient microscopic haematuria\u003C/strong\u003E that resolves on repeat testing, particularly after exercise or menstruation, does not typically require imaging. However, persistent microscopic haematuria should be investigated.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIsolated proteinuria less than 1 g/day\u003C/strong\u003E without other concerning features does not warrant immediate imaging. These patients typically require monitoring of protein excretion and kidney function over time.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOther important indications for renal ultrasound include unexplained acute kidney injury, chronic kidney disease, suspected urinary tract obstruction, and evaluation of resistant hypertension.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Renal ultrasound is indicated for unexplained acute kidney injury, haematuria, recurrent urinary tract infections, and suspected urinary tract obstruction.","Renal ultrasound can identify structural abnormalities, hydronephrosis, stones, masses, and assess kidney size and echogenicity.","Normal creatinine levels alone do not warrant renal imaging."],"references":["Singla RK, Kadatz M, Rohling R, Nguan C. Kidney Ultrasound for Nephrologists: A Review. Kidney Med. 2022 Apr 7;4(6):100464. doi: 10.1016/j.xkme.2022.100464. PMID: 35572095; PMCID: PMC9098467.","Noble VE, Brown DF. Renal ultrasound. Emerg Med Clin North Am. 2004 Aug;22(3):641-59. doi: 10.1016/j.emc.2004.04.014. PMID: 15301843.","Gulati M, Cheng J, Loo JT, Skalski M, Malhi H, Duddalwar V. Pictorial review: Renal ultrasound. Clin Imaging. 2018 Sep-Oct;51:133-154. doi: 10.1016/j.clinimag.2018.02.012. Epub 2018 Feb 16. PMID: 29477809.","Singla RK, Kadatz M, Rohling R, Nguan C. Kidney Ultrasound for Nephrologists: A Review. Kidney Med. 2022 Apr 7;4(6):100464. doi: 10.1016/j.xkme.2022.100464. PMID: 35572095; PMCID: PMC9098467."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52224"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15166"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21281"}]}}},{"type":"media","id":"21281","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21281"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/8TKp6myLbShmWMHayOIZVYre89oy7V.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/8TKp6myLbShmWMHayOIZVYre89oy7V.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":582,"height":440}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52224","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/52224"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-02T08:55:41+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-02T08:56:18+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7857"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66770"}